<p>
If you are:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>a young person with a disability wondering about your career after high school,</li>
	<li>a person with a disability who needs help preparing for, finding or holding a job,</li>
	<li>a family member or advocate of a person with a disability and want to learn about the legislation supporting the rights to services and nondiscrimination in employment,</li>
	<li>a professional working with people with disabilities or their families on issues of employment or independent living,</li>
	<li>someone injured on the job and looking for resources,</li>
</ul>
<p>
Project PRIDE may be able to assist you.
</p>


<div style="margin:40px; border:2px solid #FF9933; padding:20px;">
<p>
The Rehabilitation Act states that:<br /><br />
&quot;Disability is a natural part of human experience and in no way diminishes the right of individuals to live independently, enjoy self-determination, make choices, contribute to society, pursue meaningful careers, and enjoy full inclusion and integration in the economic, political, social, cultural, and educational mainstream of American society.&quot;<br />
<em>Section 2(a)(3) of the Rehabilitation Act</em>
</p>
</div>


<h2 class="nounderline">Project Pride Services</h2>

<p>
Information is distributed on a variety of vocational and related topics, including:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>The Rehabilitation Act, programs and services in the State of Minnesota</li>
	<li>Independent Living</li>
	<li>Post Secondary Education</li>
	<li>Americans with Disabilities Act</li>
	<li>Transition planning for youth</li>
	<li>Transportation</li>
	<li>Supported Employment and Natural Supports</li>
	<li>Vocational Rehabilitation Appeals Procedure</li>
</ul>

<h3>Services include:</h3>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Individual assistance</strong>, call a PACER advocate to discuss your concerns and questions,</li>
	<li><a href="/workshops/">Workshop presentations</a> in your community for persons with disabilities and their families or advocates; topics include the Rehabilitation Act, Americans with Disabilities Act, assistive technology, supported employment, transition, and workforce consolidation.</li>
	<li><a href="/publications/transition.asp">Publications on the Rehabilitation Act and related topics</a> for youth in transition from high school to community.</li>
	<li><strong>Culturally diverse staff</strong> to meet the needs of all persons with disabilities in the community.</li>
	<li><strong>Training for community</strong> teams consisting of professionals, families or advocates and persons with disabilities.</li>
	<li><strong>Developing more effective strategies</strong> to work with professionals in your community for team building among people with disabilities, their families and professionals. </li>
</ul>

